  "prompt": "What are the different factions within the Conservative Party?",
  "response": "The Conservative Party in the UK has several internal factions, including:\n\n1. Traditional/One Nation Conservatives\n- More centrist, moderate approach\n- Support maintaining social welfare systems\n- Favor pragmatic, less ideological policies\n\n2. Right-Wing/Libertarian Conservatives\n- Emphasize free market economics\n- Support lower taxes and reduced government intervention\n- Often Eurosceptic\n\n3. European Research Group (ERG)\n- Strong Brexit supporters\n- Advocated for a harder line in EU negotiations\n- Generally more right-wing and Eurosceptic\n\n4. One Nation Group\n- More liberal/moderate wing\n- Support social justice and inclusive policies\n- Favor remaining closer to European political traditions\n\n5. Thatcherite Conservatives\n- Follow Margaret Thatcher's economic principles\n- Support free-market economics\n- Emphasize individual responsibility\n\n6. Red Wall Conservatives\n- Represent newly won Conservative seats in traditional Labour areas\n- Focus on working-class economic interests\n- Supportive of \"levelling up\" economic policies\n\nThese factions often overlap and their influence varies depending on the current party leadership and political climate.",
